2026-03-18 | Distribute Candies in Binary Tree

	Question
Return the minimum number of moves required.

	Key Idea
Each node may have:
		extra candies (surplus)
		or need candies (deficit)

We calculate **net flow** from each subtree:
		flow = (left + right + node->val - 1)

•	If flow > 0 → extra candies to pass up  
•	If flow < 0 → needs candies from parent  

Each transfer counts as moves:
		moves += abs(left flow) + abs(right flow)

	Approach
1.	Use **postorder DFS**.
2.	Compute:
		left subtree balance
		right subtree balance
3.	Add moves:
		abs(left) + abs(right)
4.	Return:
		current balance = left + right + node->val - 1

	Time Complexity
	O(n)

	Space Complexity
	O(h)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:

    int moves = 0;

    int dfs(TreeNode* root) {

        if (!root) return 0;

        int left = dfs(root->left);
        int right = dfs(root->right);

        moves += abs(left) + abs(right);

        return root->val + left + right - 1;
    }

    int distributeCandies(TreeNode* root) {
        dfs(root);
        return moves;
    }
};

	Key Insight
Each subtree returns how many candies it needs to give or take.  
The absolute value of this flow represents the number of moves required.  
This greedy bottom-up flow ensures minimum moves.
